04274nam a22005655i 9780773558342DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735583427 a10.1515/97807735583422doi  a(DE-B1597)655670  a(OCoLC)1083130240  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBR1642.C2 7aSOC0390002bisacsh04a277.108/3qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aSchuurman, Peter J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Subversive Evangelical :bThe Ironic Charisma of an Irreligious Megachurch /cPeter J. Schuurman. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b10 photos, 2 tables, 3 diagrams  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAdvancing Studies in Religion ;v600tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tWrecking “Religion” for the Love of Jesus -- tCaught Up in the Dramatic Web -- tFrom Street Theatre to Silver City -- tIrony as Liturgy -- tLife Together -- t“Irreligious” Teamwork Backstage -- tThe “Irreligious” Paradox -- tDramaturgical Trouble and the End of the Show -- tEpilogue -- tMethod -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEvangelicals have been scandalized by their association with Donald Trump, their megachurches summarily dismissed as “religious Walmarts.” In The Subversive Evangelical Peter Schuurman shows how a growing group of “reflexive evangelicals” use irony to critique their own tradition and distinguish themselves from the stereotype of right-wing evangelicalism. Entering the Meeting House – an Ontario-based Anabaptist megachurch – as a participant observer, Schuurman discovers that the marketing is clever and the venue (a rented movie theatre) is attractive to the more than five thousand weekly attendees. But the heart of the church is its charismatic leader, Bruxy Cavey, whose anti-religious teaching and ironic tattoos offer a fresh image for evangelicals. This charisma, Schuurman argues, is not just the power of one individual; it is a dramatic production in which Cavey, his staff, and attendees cooperate, cultivating an identity as an “irreligious” megachurch and providing followers with a more culturally acceptable way to practise their faith in a secular age. Going behind the scenes to small group meetings, church dance parties, and the homes of attendees to investigate what motivates these reflexive evangelicals, Schuurman reveals a playful and provocative counterculture that distances itself from prevailing stereotypes while still embracing a conservative Christian faith.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBig churcheszCanada. 0aCharisma (Personality trait)xReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aEvangelicalismzCanada. 0aIronyxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355834240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773558342423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773558342/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles